article.description:
Tina Thompson followed one of the worst games of
her pro career with 22 points to lead the Houston Comets to an
83-76 victory over the Washington Mystics on Thursday afternoon.
article.headline: Thompson bounces back to lead Comets past Mystics
article.linkText: Thompson bounces back to lead Comets past Mystics
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Tina Thompson made up for the worst game of her
career in a big way.

Thompson scored 22 points to help the Houston Comets beat the
Washington Mystics 83-76 Thursday. She also hit a turnaround jumper
with 2:11 remaining to start a 10-0 run to end the game. Thompson
went 9-of-16, two days after scoring two points and shooting
1-of-12 in a 73-57 loss to Connecticut.

"You definitely put it behind you," Thompson said. "You can't
dwell on it, positively or negatively, or you end up wanting [the
next game] too bad."

After Thompson's turnaround, Tamecka Dixon hit a jumper from the
left side that gave the Comets a 77-76 lead, their first of the
fourth quarter. Washington never scored again after Chasity
Melvin's driving layup with 3:09 to play gave the Mystics a 76-73
advantage.

Michelle Snow added 14 points and a career-best 17 rebounds for
Houston (11-6), which won its eighth in a row at home.

Washington (8-7) has lost four of five.

The afternoon tip-off was especially early for the Comets, who
spent all day Monday traveling before their game Tuesday night,
then flew back Wednesday.

"I'm tired," Thompson said. "It was a tough trip. It's almost
like playing back-to-back."

The Comets looked tired at the start, falling behind 14-10 and
unable to stop the Mystics inside.

"I don't think people realize how tough it is to play our
schedule," said Houston forward Sheryl Swoopes, who contributed 17
points, six rebounds and four assists. "I would definitely say I'm
tired."

Melvin led the Mystics with 20 points and Alana Beard added 17,
despite leaving the game for five minutes in the third quarter with
an injured wrist.

"During the last two minutes, they made every big shot,"
Washington coach Richie Adubato said.

The Mystics outscored Houston 46-28 in the paint but couldn't
keep Snow off the boards.

"Coach said I needed to go to the offensive board a lot
harder," Snow said. "I've been watching film and analyzing and
overanalyzing. Tina put it best, 'Just go play."

Washington went ahead 58-57 on Nakia Sanford's layup with 2:47
left in the third quarter and didn't trail again until Dixon's
basket with 1:28 left in the game.

Snow had five of her rebounds in the decisive fourth quarter.

"We're showing a lot of character coming back and winning,"
Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "Snow gets 17 rebounds, and I
thought Tamecka Dixon did a nice job on Beard in the last five
minutes."
